Some preliminaries, before defining \phi _p.
The k-logarithm is defined for |z| \leqslant1 by

826Equationminus-three-points-3.2.1minus-three-points-3.2.1.xml3.2.1minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k(z)         =  \sum  z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.1}       

The \zeta (k) in the formula giving P_ { \mathrm {B}} appears in our approach as the value at 1 of \ell _k.
Let p be a prime number and consider the formal series

827Equationminus-three-points-3.2.2minus-three-points-3.2.2.xml3.2.2minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}         =  \sum _{p \nmid  n} z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.2}       

This is the Taylor series expansion of a rigid analytic function on the projective line over \mathbb {Q} _p with the open disc of radius 1 centred at 1 removed.
Indeed, we have

828Equationminus-three-points-3.2.3minus-three-points-3.2.3.xml3.2.3minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}(z)         =  \lim _N  \frac {1}{1-z^{p^N}}  \sum _{n=1, p \nmid  n}^{p^N-1} z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.3}       

From  we get the identity

829Equationminus-three-points-3.2.4minus-three-points-3.2.4.xml3.2.4minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}(1/z)         = -(-1)^k \ell _k^{(p)}(z).       \tag{3.2.4}

A formal series calculation gives, for (N,p)=1,

830Equationminus-three-points-3.2.5minus-three-points-3.2.5.xml3.2.5minus-three-points-3.2         N^{k-1} \sum _{u^N=z}  \ell _k^{(p)}(u)         =  \ell _k^{(p)}(z).       \tag{3.2.5}       

This leads us to define the "principal value" at 1

831Equationminus-three-points-3.2.6minus-three-points-3.2.6.xml3.2.6minus-three-points-3.2          \operatorname {vp} \ell _k^{(p)}(1)          \coloneqq   \frac {N^{k-1}}{1-N^{k-1}}  \sum _{ \alpha ^N=1, \alpha \neq1 }  \ell _k^{(p)}( \alpha ).       \tag{3.2.6}       

This number is independent of the choice of N coprime to p.
By , it is zero for k even.
